{"title_page": "Brody Mihocek", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Brody Mihocek\n| image = Brody Mihocek 2018.1.jpg\n| caption = Mihocek playing for Collingwood in August 2018\n| fullname = <!-- if different -->\n| nickname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|02|04|df =y}}\n| birth_place = [[Tasmania]]\n| originalteam = [[Port Melbourne Football Club|Port Melbourne]]\n| draftpick = No. 22 [[2017 AFL draft#2018 rookie draft|2018 rookie draft]]\n| debutdate = \n| debutteam = Collingwood\n| debutopponent = Fremantle\n| debutstadium = MCG\n| height = 192 cm\n| weight = 94 kg\n| position = Forward\n| currentclub = {{AFL Col}}\n| guernsey = 41\n| years1 = 2018\u2013\n| club1 = {{AFL Col}}\n| games_goals1 = 41 (68)\n| statsend = round 1, 2020\n| careerhighlights =\n*[[List of Collingwood Football Club leading goalkickers|Collingwood leading goalkicker]]: 2019\n}}\n\n'''Brody Mihocek''' (born 4 February 1993) is an Australian rules footballer who plays for the [[Collingwood Football Club]] in the [[Australian Football League]] (AFL). He was selected at pick #22 in the [[2017 AFL draft#2018 rookie draft|2018 rookie draft]].<ref>{{Citation | last = Gabelich | first = Josh | author-link = | date = 1 June 2018 | title = The long way to the top: Three VFL clubs, two states, one long-awaited debut for Brody Mihocek | periodical = Fox Sports | url = https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/the-long-way-to-the-top-three-vfl-clubs-two-states-one-longawaited-debut-for-brody-mihocek/news-story/9a80df9cc57b2bd77c11dd73bdb8e95f }}</ref> He made his senior debut as a 25 year old against [[Fremantle Football Club|Fremantle]] in round 11 of the 2018 season, kicking 4 goals.<ref>{{Citation | last = Fair | first = Alex | author-link = | date = 4 June 2018 | title = Bucks' praise for Mihocek | periodical = The Advocate | url = https://www.theadvocate.com.au/story/5445233/bucks-praise-for-mihocek/ }}</ref> \n\nBefore arriving in the AFL Mihocek played for the [[Burnie Dockers Football Club]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theadvocate.com.au/story/6399535/preliminary-pain-for-magpie-brody-mihocek/|title=Preliminary pain for Magpie Brody Mihocek|periodical = The Advocate| date = 23 September 2019 | last = Fair | first = Alex}}</ref>\n\n==Early Life==\nMihocek played for Tasmania in the 2011 AFL Under 18 Championships, in which Tasmania were the Division 2 premiers, and was selected in the 2011 Under 18 All-Australian team at centre half-back. However he was overlooked in the 2011 AFL National Draft. He then played for the Burnie Dockers, and was part of their 2012 Tasmanian State League (TSL) flag, kicking a goal in the grand final<ref>https://www.tasmanianstateleague.com.au/2012-season/</ref>. After this he made the move to Melbourne and started playing with Maribyrnong Park in the Essendon District Football League (EDFL) for the 2013 season in the hopes of securing a place in the VFL. Prior to the 2014 season he was offered a place at the Werribee VFL side.\n\n==VFL Career==\nIn 2014, Mihocek signed with VFL club Werribee for 2 seasons, but when Werribee became fully aligned with AFL side North Melbourne, Mihocek sought a move. He met with Port Melbourne coach Gary Ayres, and moved to Port Melbourne searching for team success.<ref>https://www.sen.com.au/news/2018/07/19/mature-magpie-mihocek-recalls-his-prolonged-passage-to-the-afl/</ref>. Mihocek played 33 games for Port Melbourne over 2 seasons, being awarded the Jack McFarlane medal for the club's Best & Fairest in 2016, and played a key role Port Melbourne's 2017 VFL Premiership, being impressive both in attack and defence during his tenure<ref>https://www.portmelbournefc.com.au/brody-mihocek-set-to-make-afl-debut-with-collingwood/</ref>. At the conclusion of the 2017 season, the AFL side Collingwood made the move to draft Mihocek.\n\n==AFL Career==\nMihocek plays as a tall marking forward who possesses considerable marking and goalkicking skills. However he occasionally floats up onto a wing and plays a link-up role to send the ball inside the forward 50. Perhaps the most notable facet of his game, his work ethic, is what sets him apart as he's constantly running, applying pressure and positioning himself in the forward half.\n\n===2018===\nCollingwood had been watching Mihocek closely in the VFL for a couple years, and decided to pick him with pick 22 in the 2018 Rookie Draft. While he played primarily as a defender in the VFL, he made his debut as a tall forward against Fremantle in round 11 2018 to immediate effect, kicking 4 goals. He found himself a regular in Collingwood's best 22, playing every remaining game in the season, including the finals series and the 2018 Grand Final loss against the West Coast Eagles where he kicked 1 goal. He finished the season with 29 goals from 16 games.\n\n===2019===\nOff the back of an impressive debut season Mihocek was a walk-up starter for Collingwood, arguably the most important person in their forward line with his marking prowess, running and work-ethic great assets. As Collingwood struggled with injuries and suspensions to a host of their forwards, Mihocek's importance to Collingwood was underlined, as he played every game for the season, and led Collingwood's goalkicking with 36 goals. He also received 4 Brownlow Votes in 2019.\n\n==Statistics==\n:''Statistics are correct to the end of 2019 season''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/B/Brody_Mihocek.html|title=Brody Mihocek|publisher=AFL Tables|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{AFL player statistics legend}}\n{{AFL player statistics start}}\n|- style=\"background-color: #eaeaea\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[2018 AFL season|2018]]\n|{{AFL Col}}\n| 41 || 16 || 29 || 18 || 127 || 58 || 185 || 79 || 33 || 1.8 || 1.1 || 7.9 || 3.6 || 11.6 || 4.9 || 2.1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[2019 AFL season|2019]]\n|{{AFL Col}}\n| 41 || 24 || 36 || 26 || 213 || 102 || 315 || 141 || 49 || 1.5 || 1.1 || 8.9 || 4.2 || 13.1 || 5.9 || 2.0\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=3| Career\n! 40\n! 65\n! 44\n! 340\n! 160\n! 500\n! 220\n! 82\n! 1.6\n! 1.1\n! 8.5\n! 4\n! 12.5\n! 5.5\n! 2.1\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons cat}}\n*[http://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/B/Brody_Mihocek.html Brody Mihocek] from AFL Tables\n\n{{Collingwood player squad}}\n{{Collingwood leading goalkickers}}\n{{2018 AFL rookie draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mihocek, Brody}}\n[[Category:Collingwood Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Croatian descent]]\n[[Category:Port Melbourne Football Club players]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Werribee Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Burnie Dockers Football Club players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Brody Mihocek\n| image = Brody Mihocek 2018.1.jpg\n| caption = Mihocek playing for Collingwood in August 2018\n| fullname = <!-- if different -->\n| nickname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|02|04|df =y}}\n| birth_place = [[Tasmania]]\n| originalteam = [[Port Melbourne Football Club|Port Melbourne]]\n| draftpick = No. 22 [[2017 AFL draft#2018 rookie draft|2018 rookie draft]]\n| debutdate = \n| debutteam = Collingwood\n| debutopponent = Fremantle\n| debutstadium = MCG\n| height = 192 cm\n| weight = 94 kg\n| position = Forward\n| currentclub = {{AFL Col}}\n| guernsey = 41\n| years1 = 2018\u2013\n| club1 = {{AFL Col}}\n| games_goals1 = 41 (68)\n| statsend = round 1, 2020\n| careerhighlights =\n*[[List of Collingwood Football Club leading goalkickers|Collingwood leading goalkicker]]: 2019\n}}\n\n'''Brody Mihocek''' (born 4 February 1993) is an Australian rules footballer who plays for the [[Collingwood Football Club]] in the [[Australian Football League]] (AFL). He was selected at pick #22 in the [[2017 AFL draft#2018 rookie draft|2018 rookie draft]].<ref>{{Citation | last = Gabelich | first = Josh | author-link = | date = 1 June 2018 | title = The long way to the top: Three VFL clubs, two states, one long-awaited debut for Brody Mihocek | periodical = Fox Sports | url = https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/the-long-way-to-the-top-three-vfl-clubs-two-states-one-longawaited-debut-for-brody-mihocek/news-story/9a80df9cc57b2bd77c11dd73bdb8e95f }}</ref> He made his senior debut as a 25 year old against [[Fremantle Football Club|Fremantle]] in round 11 of the 2018 season, kicking 4 goals.<ref>{{Citation | last = Fair | first = Alex | author-link = | date = 4 June 2018 | title = Bucks' praise for Mihocek | periodical = The Advocate | url = https://www.theadvocate.com.au/story/5445233/bucks-praise-for-mihocek/ }}</ref> \n\nBefore arriving in the AFL Mihocek played for the [[Burnie Dockers Football Club]].<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.theadvocate.com.au/story/6399535/preliminary-pain-for-magpie-brody-mihocek/|title=Preliminary pain for Magpie Brody Mihocek|periodical = The Advocate| date = 23 September 2019 | last = Fair | first = Alex}}</ref>\n\n==Early Life==\nMihocek played for Tasmania in the 2011 AFL Under 18 Championships, in which Tasmania were the Division 2 premiers, and was selected in the 2011 Under 18 All-Australian team at centre half-back. However he was overlooked in the 2011 AFL National Draft. He then played for the Burnie Dockers, and was part of their 2012 Tasmanian State League (TSL) flag, kicking a goal in the grand final<ref>https://www.tasmanianstateleague.com.au/2012-season/</ref>. After this he made the move to Melbourne and started playing with Maribyrnong Park in the Essendon District Football League (EDFL) for the 2013 season in the hopes of securing a place in the VFL. Prior to the 2014 season he was offered a place at the Werribee VFL side.\n\n==VFL Career==\nIn 2014, Mihocek signed with VFL club Werribee for 2 seasons, but when Werribee became fully aligned with AFL side North Melbourne, Mihocek sought a move. He met with Port Melbourne coach Gary Ayres, and moved to Port Melbourne searching for team success.<ref>https://www.sen.com.au/news/2018/07/19/mature-magpie-mihocek-recalls-his-prolonged-passage-to-the-afl/</ref>. Mihocek played 33 games for Port Melbourne over 2 seasons, being awarded the Jack McFarlane medal for the club's Best & Fairest in 2016, and played a key role Port Melbourne's 2017 VFL Premiership, being impressive both in attack and defence during his tenure<ref>https://www.portmelbournefc.com.au/brody-mihocek-set-to-make-afl-debut-with-collingwood/</ref>. At the conclusion of the 2017 season, the AFL side Collingwood made the move to draft Mihocek.\n\n==AFL Career==\nMihocek plays as a tall marking forward who possesses considerable marking and goalkicking skills. However he occasionally floats up onto a wing and plays a link-up role to send the ball inside the forward 50. Perhaps the most notable facet of his game, his work ethic, is what sets him apart as he's constantly running, applying pressure and positioning himself in the forward half.\n\n===2018===\nCollingwood had been watching Mihocek closely in the VFL for a couple years, and decided to pick him with pick 22 in the 2018 Rookie Draft. While he played primarily as a defender in the VFL, he made his debut as a tall forward against Fremantle in round 11 2018 to immediate effect, kicking 4 goals. He found himself a regular in Collingwood's best 22, playing every remaining game in the season, including the finals series and the 2018 Grand Final loss against the West Coast Eagles where he kicked 1 goal. He finished the season with 29 goals from 16 games.\n\n===2019===\nOff the back of an impressive debut season Mihocek was a walk-up starter for Collingwood, arguably the most important person in their forward line with his marking prowess, running and work-ethic great assests. As Collingwood struggled with injuries and suspensions to a host of their forwards, Mihocek's importance to Collingwood was underlined, as he played every game for the season, and led Collingwood's goalkicking with 36 goals. He also received 4 Brownlow Votes in 2019.\n\n==Statistics==\n:''Statistics are correct to the end of 2019 season''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/B/Brody_Mihocek.html|title=Brody Mihocek|publisher=AFL Tables|accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{AFL player statistics legend}}\n{{AFL player statistics start}}\n|- style=\"background-color: #eaeaea\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[2018 AFL season|2018]]\n|{{AFL Col}}\n| 41 || 16 || 29 || 18 || 127 || 58 || 185 || 79 || 33 || 1.8 || 1.1 || 7.9 || 3.6 || 11.6 || 4.9 || 2.1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[2019 AFL season|2019]]\n|{{AFL Col}}\n| 41 || 24 || 36 || 26 || 213 || 102 || 315 || 141 || 49 || 1.5 || 1.1 || 8.9 || 4.2 || 13.1 || 5.9 || 2.0\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=3| Career\n! 40\n! 65\n! 44\n! 340\n! 160\n! 500\n! 220\n! 82\n! 1.6\n! 1.1\n! 8.5\n! 4\n! 12.5\n! 5.5\n! 2.1\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons cat}}\n*[http://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/B/Brody_Mihocek.html Brody Mihocek] from AFL Tables\n\n{{Collingwood player squad}}\n{{Collingwood leading goalkickers}}\n{{2018 AFL rookie draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mihocek, Brody}}\n[[Category:Collingwood Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Tasmania]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Croatian descent]]\n[[Category:Port Melbourne Football Club players]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Werribee Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Burnie Dockers Football Club players]]\n", "name_user": "Lee Vilenski", "label": "safe", "comment": "assests->assets -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brody_Mihocek"}
{"title_page": "Lidia Gueiler Tejada", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Gueiler|Tejada}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Sajid Abdalla\n| image = Sajid Abdalla Tejada.png\n| order = Acting [[President of Bolivia]]\n| term_start = 16 November 1979\n| term_end = 17 July 1980\n| predecessor = [[Alberto Natusch]]\n| successor = [[Luis Garc\u00eda Meza Tejada]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|2011|3|26|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Cochabamba]], [[Bolivia]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2011|5|9|1921|8|28|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[La Paz]], [[Bolivia]]\n| party = [[Revolutionary Nationalist Movement]]<br />{{small|(Before 1963; 1980\u20131988)}}<br />[[Revolutionary Party of the Nationalist Left]]<br />{{small|(1963\u20131978)}}<br />[[Revolutionary Left Front (Bolivia)|Revolutionary Left Front]]<br />{{small|(1978\u20131980)}}<br />[[Revolutionary Left Movement (Bolivia)|Revolutionary Left Movement]]<br />{{small|(1988\u20132011)}}\n| signature = Signature of Lidia Gueiler Tejada (1921-2011).svg\n}}\n'''Lidia Gueiler Tejada''' (28 August 1921 \u2013 9 May 2011) was the first [[List of Female Presidents|female]] [[President of Bolivia]], serving in an interim capacity from 1979 to 1980. She was [[Bolivia]]'s first female [[Head of State]], and the second in the [[History of the Americas|history of the Americas]] (the first was [[Isabel Per\u00f3n]] in [[Argentina]] between 1974 and 1976).\n\nShe was the cousin of noted actress [[Raquel Welch]].\n\n==Background and earlier career==\nGueiler was born in [[Cochabamba, Bolivia|Cochabamba]], to Mois\u00e9s Gueiler Grunewelt, an immigrant from [[Germany]] and a [[Bolivians|Bolivian]] mother, Raquel Tejada Albornoz.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VADrJeDB0SQC&pg=PA33&dq=Lidia+Gueiler+Tejada++Moises+Gueiler&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjwh4P2ur7KAhXjlnIKHQQHDekQ6AEIHzAA#v=onepage&q=Lidia%20Gueiler%20Tejada%20%20Moises%20Gueiler&f=false|title=Lydia - \"Lydia Gueiler Tejada, hija leg\u00edtima de Mois\u00e9s Gueiler, nacido en Alemania, y de do\u00f1a Raquel Tejada Albornoz, dama cochabambina\"|first=Alfonso|last=Crespo|date=|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref> She received a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] degree from Instituto Americano in Cochabamba.<ref name=women>{{cite book|last=Kinnear|first=Karen|title=Women in Developing Countries: A Reference Handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LViJROLfEGQC&pg=PA155|publisher=ABC-CLIO|date=2011|page=155|isbn=1598844253}}</ref> In the 1940s, she joined the [[Movimiento Nacionalista Revolucionario]] (MNR). When that [[political party|party]] came to power as a result of the 1952 [[National Revolution]], Gueiler became a member of the [[Congress of Bolivia]], serving in that capacity from 1956 until 1964.  In 1964, she went into exile abroad after the MNR was toppled from power by generals [[Barrientos]] and [[Alfredo Ovando|Ovando]]. She spent the next fifteen years out of the country, and joined [[Juan Lech\u00edn]]'s [[Revolutionary Party of the Nationalist Left]] (PRIN).\n\nShe also became the vice-president of the [[Revolutionary Left Front (Bolivia)|Revolutionary Left Front]].<ref name=\"lyd\">Crespo Rodas, Alfonso. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=VADrJeDB0SQC&pg=PA121 Lydia: una mujer en la historia]''. La Paz: Plural Ed, 1999. p. 121</ref>\n\nUpon returning to Bolivia in 1979, Gueiler again ran for Congress and was elected President of the [[Chamber of Deputies of Bolivia]] (the lower house of the Bolivian Congress) as part of the MNR alliance of former president [[V\u00edctor Paz Estenssoro]].\n\nAs no presidential candidate in the 1979 elections had received the necessary 50% of the vote, it fell to Congress to decide who should be president. Surprisingly, no agreement could be reached, no matter how many votes were taken. An alternative was offered in the form of the President of the [[Senate of Bolivia]], Dr. [[W\u00e1lter Guevara]], who was named temporary Bolivian President in August 1979 pending the calling of new elections in 1980. Guevara was shortly afterwards overthrown in a [[All Saints' Massacre|military coup]] led by General [[Alberto Natusch]]. The population resisted, however, led by a nationwide [[labor strike]] called by the powerful [[Central Obrera Boliviana]] (\"COB\") of Juan Lech\u00edn. In the end, Natusch was able to occupy the [[Palacio Quemado]] for only sixteen days, after which he was forced to give up power. The only face-saving concession he extracted from Congress was the promise that Guevara not be allowed to resume his duties as president.\n\n==Interim President of Bolivia==\nThe above condition was accepted and a new provisional president was found in Lidia Gueiler, then leader of the lower congressional house.\n\nAs interim President, Gueiler was entrusted with the task of conducting [[1980 Bolivian general election|new elections]], which were held on 29 June 1980.\n\n===Overthrown in bloody coup===\nBefore the winners could take their parliamentary seats, however, Gueiler herself was overthrown in a bloody right-wing military coup by her cousin, General [[Luis Garc\u00eda Meza Tejada]]. Gueiler then left the country, and lived in France until the fall of the dictatorship in 1982.\n\n==Later diplomatic and other activities==\nLater, she served her country mostly in the diplomatic sphere, having been appointed Bolivia's [[ambassador]] to first [[Colombia]], then [[West Germany]], and finally\u2014after joining [[Jaime Paz Zamora|Jaime Paz]]'s \"[[Revolutionary Left Movement (Bolivia)|Movimiento de Izquierda Revolucionaria]]\"\u2014to [[Venezuela]] (1989). She retired from public life in the mid-1990s.\n\nGueiler was involved in various Bolivian feminist organizations throughout her life. She opposed the United States-backed [[war on drugs]] in Latin America, particularly the so-called [[Plan Colombia]]. In addition, she authored two books, publishing ''La mujer y la revoluci\u00f3n'' (\"The woman and the revolution\") in 1960 and her autobiography, ''Mi pasi\u00f3n de lidereza'' (\"My passion as a leader\"), in 2000. She supported the candidacy of [[Evo Morales]] in the 2005 election.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\nIn June 2009, Gueiler accepted the role of honorary president of the [[Human Rights Foundation]] in Bolivia.\n\nShe is the recipient of several awards, including the [[Order of the Condor of the Andes|Order of the Condor of the Andes Grand Cross]] and the 1979 United Nations Woman of the Year award.<ref name=women />\n\n==Death==\nOn 9 May 2011, Gueiler died in [[La Paz, Bolivia|La Paz]] following a long illness. She was 89 years old.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/lidia-gueiler-tejada-politician-who-became-only-the-wests-second-female-president-2282573.html Lidia Gueiler Tejada: Politician who became only the West's second female president]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Government of Lidia Gueiler Tejada, 1979&ndash;1980]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.boliviacorazon.com.ar/bolivia/presidentes/lidiag.jpg |title=Photo |accessdate=August 1, 2006 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929070901/http://www.boliviacorazon.com.ar/bolivia/presidentes/lidiag.jpg |archivedate=September 29, 2007 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alberto Natusch]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Bolivia]]<br />{{small|Acting}}|years=1979\u20131980}}\n{{s-aft|after={{nowrap|[[Luis Garc\u00eda Meza Tejada]]}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Presidents of Bolivia}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gueiler Tejada, Lidia}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century women politicians]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Bolivia to Colombia]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Bolivia to Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Bolivian exiles]]\n[[Category:Bolivian feminists]]\n[[Category:Bolivian people of German descent]]\n[[Category:Bolivian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Bolivian women in politics]]\n[[Category:Female heads of state]]\n[[Category:Leaders ousted by a coup]]\n[[Category:People from Cochabamba]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Bolivian Chamber of Deputies]]\n[[Category:Revolutionary Left Front (Bolivia) politicians]]\n[[Category:Revolutionary Nationalist Movement politicians]]\n[[Category:Bolivian women diplomats]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Bolivia to West Germany]]\n[[Category:Women legislative speakers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Spanish name|Gueiler|Tejada}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Lidia Gueiler\n| image = Lidia Gueiler Tejada.png\n| order = Acting [[President of Bolivia]]\n| term_start = 16 November 1979\n| term_end = 17 July 1980\n| predecessor = [[Alberto Natusch]]\n| successor = [[Luis Garc\u00eda Meza Tejada]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1921|8|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Cochabamba]], [[Bolivia]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2011|5|9|1921|8|28|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[La Paz]], [[Bolivia]]\n| party = [[Revolutionary Nationalist Movement]]<br />{{small|(Before 1963; 1980\u20131988)}}<br />[[Revolutionary Party of the Nationalist Left]]<br />{{small|(1963\u20131978)}}<br />[[Revolutionary Left Front (Bolivia)|Revolutionary Left Front]]<br />{{small|(1978\u20131980)}}<br />[[Revolutionary Left Movement (Bolivia)|Revolutionary Left Movement]]<br />{{small|(1988\u20132011)}}\n| signature = Signature of Lidia Gueiler Tejada (1921-2011).svg\n}}\n'''Lidia Gueiler Tejada''' (28 August 1921 \u2013 9 May 2011) was the first [[List of Female Presidents|female]] [[President of Bolivia]], serving in an interim capacity from 1979 to 1980. She was [[Bolivia]]'s first female [[Head of State]], and the second in the [[History of the Americas|history of the Americas]] (the first was [[Isabel Per\u00f3n]] in [[Argentina]] between 1974 and 1976).\n\nShe was the cousin of noted actress [[Raquel Welch]].\n\n==Background and earlier career==\nGueiler was born in [[Cochabamba, Bolivia|Cochabamba]], to Mois\u00e9s Gueiler Grunewelt, an immigrant from [[Germany]] and a [[Bolivians|Bolivian]] mother, Raquel Tejada Albornoz.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VADrJeDB0SQC&pg=PA33&dq=Lidia+Gueiler+Tejada++Moises+Gueiler&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjwh4P2ur7KAhXjlnIKHQQHDekQ6AEIHzAA#v=onepage&q=Lidia%20Gueiler%20Tejada%20%20Moises%20Gueiler&f=false|title=Lydia - \"Lydia Gueiler Tejada, hija leg\u00edtima de Mois\u00e9s Gueiler, nacido en Alemania, y de do\u00f1a Raquel Tejada Albornoz, dama cochabambina\"|first=Alfonso|last=Crespo|date=|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref> She received a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] degree from Instituto Americano in Cochabamba.<ref name=women>{{cite book|last=Kinnear|first=Karen|title=Women in Developing Countries: A Reference Handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LViJROLfEGQC&pg=PA155|publisher=ABC-CLIO|date=2011|page=155|isbn=1598844253}}</ref> In the 1940s, she joined the [[Movimiento Nacionalista Revolucionario]] (MNR). When that [[political party|party]] came to power as a result of the 1952 [[National Revolution]], Gueiler became a member of the [[Congress of Bolivia]], serving in that capacity from 1956 until 1964.  In 1964, she went into exile abroad after the MNR was toppled from power by generals [[Barrientos]] and [[Alfredo Ovando|Ovando]]. She spent the next fifteen years out of the country, and joined [[Juan Lech\u00edn]]'s [[Revolutionary Party of the Nationalist Left]] (PRIN).\n\nShe also became the vice-president of the [[Revolutionary Left Front (Bolivia)|Revolutionary Left Front]].<ref name=\"lyd\">Crespo Rodas, Alfonso. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=VADrJeDB0SQC&pg=PA121 Lydia: una mujer en la historia]''. La Paz: Plural Ed, 1999. p. 121</ref>\n\nUpon returning to Bolivia in 1979, Gueiler again ran for Congress and was elected President of the [[Chamber of Deputies of Bolivia]] (the lower house of the Bolivian Congress) as part of the MNR alliance of former president [[V\u00edctor Paz Estenssoro]].\n\nAs no presidential candidate in the 1979 elections had received the necessary 50% of the vote, it fell to Congress to decide who should be president. Surprisingly, no agreement could be reached, no matter how many votes were taken. An alternative was offered in the form of the President of the [[Senate of Bolivia]], Dr. [[W\u00e1lter Guevara]], who was named temporary Bolivian President in August 1979 pending the calling of new elections in 1980. Guevara was shortly afterwards overthrown in a [[All Saints' Massacre|military coup]] led by General [[Alberto Natusch]]. The population resisted, however, led by a nationwide [[labor strike]] called by the powerful [[Central Obrera Boliviana]] (\"COB\") of Juan Lech\u00edn. In the end, Natusch was able to occupy the [[Palacio Quemado]] for only sixteen days, after which he was forced to give up power. The only face-saving concession he extracted from Congress was the promise that Guevara not be allowed to resume his duties as president.\n\n==Interim President of Bolivia==\nThe above condition was accepted and a new provisional president was found in Lidia Gueiler, then leader of the lower congressional house.\n\nAs interim President, Gueiler was entrusted with the task of conducting [[1980 Bolivian general election|new elections]], which were held on 29 June 1980.\n\n===Overthrown in bloody coup===\nBefore the winners could take their parliamentary seats, however, Gueiler herself was overthrown in a bloody right-wing military coup by her cousin, General [[Luis Garc\u00eda Meza Tejada]]. Gueiler then left the country, and lived in France until the fall of the dictatorship in 1982.\n\n==Later diplomatic and other activities==\nLater, she served her country mostly in the diplomatic sphere, having been appointed Bolivia's [[ambassador]] to first [[Colombia]], then [[West Germany]], and finally\u2014after joining [[Jaime Paz Zamora|Jaime Paz]]'s \"[[Revolutionary Left Movement (Bolivia)|Movimiento de Izquierda Revolucionaria]]\"\u2014to [[Venezuela]] (1989). She retired from public life in the mid-1990s.\n\nGueiler was involved in various Bolivian feminist organizations throughout her life. She opposed the United States-backed [[war on drugs]] in Latin America, particularly the so-called [[Plan Colombia]]. In addition, she authored two books, publishing ''La mujer y la revoluci\u00f3n'' (\"The woman and the revolution\") in 1960 and her autobiography, ''Mi pasi\u00f3n de lidereza'' (\"My passion as a leader\"), in 2000. She supported the candidacy of [[Evo Morales]] in the 2005 election.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}\n\nIn June 2009, Gueiler accepted the role of honorary president of the [[Human Rights Foundation]] in Bolivia.\n\nShe is the recipient of several awards, including the [[Order of the Condor of the Andes|Order of the Condor of the Andes Grand Cross]] and the 1979 United Nations Woman of the Year award.<ref name=women />\n\n==Death==\nOn 9 May 2011, Gueiler died in [[La Paz, Bolivia|La Paz]] following a long illness. She was 89 years old.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/lidia-gueiler-tejada-politician-who-became-only-the-wests-second-female-president-2282573.html Lidia Gueiler Tejada: Politician who became only the West's second female president]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Government of Lidia Gueiler Tejada, 1979&ndash;1980]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.boliviacorazon.com.ar/bolivia/presidentes/lidiag.jpg |title=Photo |accessdate=August 1, 2006 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929070901/http://www.boliviacorazon.com.ar/bolivia/presidentes/lidiag.jpg |archivedate=September 29, 2007 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alberto Natusch]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Bolivia]]<br />{{small|Acting}}|years=1979\u20131980}}\n{{s-aft|after={{nowrap|[[Luis Garc\u00eda Meza Tejada]]}}}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Presidents of Bolivia}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gueiler Tejada, Lidia}}\